<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910624-0024</DOCNO><DOCID>910624-0024.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Raytheon Co.:   Layoffs of 700 Workers Set   For Missile Systems Division</HL><DATE>06/24/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   RTN</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)DIVERSIFIED TECHNOLOGY (DTC)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><RE>ARABIAN PENINSULA (ARA)EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)ISRAEL (ISR)MASSACHUSETTS (MA)MIDDLE EAST (ML)NORTH AMERICA (NME)SAUDI ARABIA (SA)TURKEY (TU)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Raytheon Co., Lexington, Mass., will lay off about 700people in its missile systems division, including 250 workersat one of the company's Patriot missile manufacturing plants,a spokesman said.   The layoffs reflect in part a return to normal workschedules following a period of accelerated production inresponse to the Persian Gulf War, the spokesman said. He alsosaid the cuts reflect a decline in current and anticipateddefense spending and would affect engineers, manufacturingand office personnel and managers.</LP><TEXT>   Separately, the big aircraft, appliance, and missile makersaid the missile systems unit won a $346.3 million Armycontract for 647 Patriot missiles. The contract includes newfunding for 347 missiles, including 32 each for Turkey andIsrael, and finalizes funding for 300 Patriot missiles forSaudi Arabia, Raytheon said.   The layoffs will be centered in the Andover, Lowell andTewksbury production and engineering sites in Massachusetts.Raytheon's world payroll will fall to 74,100 with thecutbacks, a spokesman said.</TEXT></DOC>